"## Abstract\nNon-Lambertian light field depth estimation remains a fundamental challenge, as complex material reflections fundamentally violate the view consistency assumption. Current methods based on implicit epipolar plane image (EPI) networks heavily rely on data-driven feature extraction, resulting in severe depth ambiguity and texture-copying artifacts (e.g., Mean Absolute Error > 0.41) in specular or scattering regions. To address these limitations, a unified dual-mask physical model was proposed for robust depth recovery. Specifically, a medium mask and an angular-direction mask were introduced to physically quantify surface roughness and characterize the wave-vector deflection field. By utilizing an MRI-inspired 2-D discrete Fourier transform (2D-DFT) to map 81 angular samples into spectral distributions, the model explicitly parsed pixel-level material properties. Furthermore, a multi-scale angular cost volume network (MACVO-Net) was designed to exploit all 81 views, where the cost volume flatness naturally served as an uncertainty indicator for non-Lambertian regions. Through guided training, depth predictions from different regions were component-awarely fused using physically derived Bidirectional Reflectance Distribution Function (BRDF) weights. Extensive experiments demonstrate that the proposed physical priors effectively eliminated EPI ambiguities, significantly improving the reflective energy contrast ratio by up to 495.8% and achieving robust performance across complex scenes. This framework provides a physically interpretable solution, successfully breaking the accuracy bottleneck of pure geometry matching in non-Lambertian domains.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian reflection, Dual-mask physical model, Multi-scale angular cost volume, Material classification"